  "prompt": "Which are the best books to learn C?",
  "response": "There are several highly recommended books for learning C programming, catering to different levels of expertise. Here are some of the best:\n\n1. **\"The C Programming Language\" by Brian W. Kernighan and Dennis M. Ritchie**\n   - Often referred to as K&R, this book is considered the bible for C programmers. Written by the creators of C, it provides a comprehensive and authoritative introduction to the language.\n\n2. **\"C Programming Absolute Beginner's Guide\" by Greg Perry and Dean Miller**\n   - This book is great for beginners, providing clear explanations and practical examples to help newcomers understand the basics of C programming.\n\n3. **\"Head First C\" by David Griffiths and Dawn Griffiths**\n   - Known for its engaging and visually rich approach, this book teaches C programming concepts in a fun and interactive way.\n\n4. **\"Programming in C\" by Stephen G. Kochan**\n   - This book is another excellent resource for beginners. It covers fundamental concepts and provides plenty of examples to practice.\n\n5. **\"C Primer Plus\" by Stephen Prata**\n   - Suitable for both novices and more experienced programmers, this book offers thorough coverage of C programming with numerous exercises and examples.\n\n6. **\"Expert C Programming: Deep C Secrets\" by Peter van der Linden**\n   - This book is geared towards experienced programmers who want to deepen their understanding of C. It covers advanced topics and provides insights into the intricacies of the language.\n\n7. **\"C in a Nutshell\" by Peter Prinz and Tony Crawford**\n   - Ideal for intermediate to advanced programmers, this book serves as a reference guide for quick lookup and detailed explanations of C concepts and syntax.\n\n8. **\"Let Us C\" by Yashavant Kanetkar**\n   - Popular in India, this book is another great resource for beginners, providing detailed explanations, exercises, and practice problems.\n\nEach book has its own strengths, so the best one for you will depend on your current level of expertise and learning preferences.",
